have been changed.

00:31:54.410 --> 00:31:56.534
Now some practical advice,

00:31:56.534 --> 00:31:59.370
where to kind of help you
get started.

00:32:01.870 --> 00:32:05.010
And to be fair, most of this
advice is

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:08.890
looking through the sort of
lens of retrospect, which

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:12.130
means that, that this is not
always how things happen.

00:32:12.130 --> 00:32:13.940
But I can look back in time
and say,

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:16.090
these are things that led
certain things to be true.

00:32:16.090 --> 00:32:18.990
So it&#39;s hard to be super
deterministic about building

00:32:18.990 --> 00:32:22.110
a company, and you might not
have all of these things

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:22.943
totally figured out.

00:32:22.943 --> 00:32:24.330
But these will give you a
sense of some of

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:27.270
the patterns to recognize
and

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:29.670
opportunities to exploit as
you&#39;re building, or

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:31.805
thinking about building, an
enterprise software company.

00:32:31.805 --> 00:32:35.890
So the first is, spot
technology disruptions.

00:32:35.890 --> 00:32:36.540
And this is gonna be

00:32:36.540 --> 00:32:38.950
true whether you&#39;re building
consumer or enterprise.

00:32:38.950 --> 00:32:40.260
The rest are more enterprise
oriented, but

00:32:40.260 --> 00:32:43.010
this is just fundamental to
entrepreneurship,

00:32:43.010 --> 00:32:44.610
if you&#39;re gonna build a tech
company.

00:32:44.610 --> 00:32:48.612
So you have to look for new
enabling technologies or

00:32:48.612 --> 00:32:52.337
major trends, like
fundamental trends, that

00:32:52.337 --> 00:32:56.432
create a wide gap between
how things have been done,

00:32:56.432 --> 00:32:58.990
and how they can be done.

00:32:58.990 --> 00:33:02.670
And so, looking back in time
at our business, the gap was

00:33:02.670 --> 00:33:06.260
basically, storage is
getting cheaper, internet

00:33:06.260 --> 00:33:08.520
was getting faster, browsers
were getting better.

00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:10.840
Yet we&#39;re still sharing
files through this

00:33:10.840 --> 00:33:13.990
very complicated, very
esoteric, very slow and

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:15.200
cumbersome means.

00:33:15.200 --> 00:33:20.000
So any time where the delta
between what is possible and

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:22.480
how things work today is at
its widest,

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:25.550
that is an opportunity to go
build new technology to go

00:33:25.550 --> 00:33:26.940
solve a problem.

00:33:26.940 --> 00:33:29.170
And so as you&#39;re looking at
the enterprise,

00:33:29.170 --> 00:33:32.230
the question is, what about
the cost of computing

00:33:32.230 --> 00:33:35.680
dropping so rapidly changes
what enterprises can

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:36.300
do with their data?

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:38.030
What does it change about
what you

00:33:38.030 --> 00:33:40.390
can do from a business model
standpoint?

00:33:40.390 --> 00:33:44.150
What was impossible, because
of either

00:33:44.150 --> 00:33:47.660
economic feasibility or
technical feasibility 10 or

00:33:47.660 --> 00:33:50.890
15 years ago, that now all
of a sudden is possible.

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:52.440
And a fun thing you can do
sometime is,

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:57.140
if you go look at articles
from like the 1990&#39;s or

00:33:57.140 --> 00:33:59.810
even the 1980&#39;s, business
articles about technology.

00:34:01.070 --> 00:34:03.580
All we&#39;re really doing is
repeating a lot of

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:07.300
the technologies that were
tried 10, 20, 30 years ago.

00:34:07.300 --> 00:34:09.200
It&#39;s just, it was too
expensive,

00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:10.740
it was too unusable, and we
didn&#39;t have

00:34:10.740 --> 00:34:13.460
the enabling technologies to
make it possible.

00:34:13.460 --> 00:34:16.280
So you can kind of see this
pattern emerge constantly

00:34:16.280 --> 00:34:18.420
where something that was
impossible five or 10 years

00:34:18.420 --> 00:34:21.030
ago, all of a sudden becomes
very practical.

00:34:21.030 --> 00:34:22.720
So I&#39;ll give you an example.

00:34:22.720 --> 00:34:23.790
There&#39;s a company called
PlanGrid.

00:34:23.790 --> 00:34:26.140
Does anybody know what
PlanGrid does?

00:34:26.140 --> 00:34:26.660
Okay.
Cool.

00:34:26.660 --> 00:34:28.530
Are you in the construction
industry?

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:29.660
You are?

00:34:29.660 --> 00:34:30.250
&gt;&gt; Yes, I am.

00:34:30.250 --> 00:34:32.040
&gt;&gt; Oh, my god.
What does that even mean?

00:34:32.040 --> 00:34:34.030
&gt;&gt; In terms of PlanGrid or
like in construction?

00:34:34.030 --> 00:34:34.530
&gt;&gt; Construction.

00:34:35.850 --> 00:34:37.140
&gt;&gt; I work at a job site.

00:34:37.140 --> 00:34:38.470
We build buildings.

00:34:38.470 --> 00:34:40.107
&gt;&gt; Holy crap, that&#39;s great.

00:34:40.107 --> 00:34:41.641
&gt;&gt; Okay, so.

00:34:41.641 --> 00:34:42.938
Thank you.

00:34:42.938 --> 00:34:48.817
So basically PlanGrid is a
mobile application that

00:34:48.817 --> 00:34:53.610
lets you manage construction
projects.

00:34:53.610 --> 00:34:55.988
Lets you get access to your
blueprints, lets you manage

00:34:55.988 --> 00:34:58.320
all of the data around a
construction process.

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:03.230
And what this team realized
was that $4 billion,

00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:06.270
I believe, are spent every
