00:35:06.270 --> 00:35:08.010
and making all of the
prints, and

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:09.896
updates to those blueprints
any time there&#39;s a change.

00:35:09.896 --> 00:35:11.190
And then that has to ripple
and

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:14.830
cascade through a very wide
network of contractors and

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:16.170
construction people every
time that

00:35:16.170 --> 00:35:18.208
there&#39;s even just one
slight, minute change.

00:35:18.208 --> 00:35:20.646
And they realized that, you
know, with the iPad,

00:35:20.646 --> 00:35:23.138
all of a sudden, we have the
perfect form vector to be

00:35:23.138 --> 00:35:25.424
able to load up blueprints
and load up content.

00:35:25.424 --> 00:35:26.568
And this is something that

00:35:26.568 --> 00:35:28.804
could ripple through the
construction industry,

00:35:28.804 --> 00:35:30.936
which isn&#39;t necessarily
notoriously known for

00:35:30.936 --> 00:35:33.510
high technology, except for
on the design side.

00:35:33.510 --> 00:35:34.980
How could they build
technology that would

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:38.580
make the data access, the
data collaboration problem

00:35:38.580 --> 00:35:42.050
really, really seamless and
easy to do, in a very,

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:43.330
you know, traditional
industry that

00:35:43.330 --> 00:35:46.590
hasn&#39;t quite changed for a
while.

00:35:46.590 --> 00:35:50.800
So it was a sort of perfect,
sort of discovery of

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:53.280
a technology change in a
market and

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:55.780
figuring out how do those
two things converge.

00:35:55.780 --> 00:35:58.100
And then this team built a
great startup out of it that

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:01.830
is doing incredibly well,
and totally taking over

00:36:01.830 --> 00:36:04.576
the construction industry as
proven by this individual.

00:36:04.576 --> 00:36:06.400
Thank you.

00:36:08.458 --> 00:36:11.230
&gt;&gt; So the next thing is, in
the enterprise you want to

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:12.880
start intentionally small.

00:36:13.890 --> 00:36:17.060
What I mean by that is, you
want to find, and

00:36:17.060 --> 00:36:18.740
this is again, true of a lot
of companies, but

00:36:18.740 --> 00:36:20.230
even more true in
enterprise,

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:22.150
in a user-led paradigm.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:25.640
You want to find the wedge
that is sort of the very

00:36:25.640 --> 00:36:29.000
natural place where you can
create a product that will

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:32.420
slip in between the gaps of
other existing products.

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:33.340
But is something that you

00:36:33.340 --> 00:36:35.190
think over time expands to
become

00:36:35.190 --> 00:36:38.140
a more important part of the
enterprise architecture.

00:36:38.140 --> 00:36:41.140
So, what you want to start
to do is to say,

00:36:41.140 --> 00:36:43.510
we&#39;re gonna take this sliver
of a problem,

00:36:43.510 --> 00:36:46.680
we&#39;re going to totally make
the user experience on

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:48.010
that incredible.

00:36:48.010 --> 00:36:49.990
We&#39;re gonna either change
the business model.

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:52.360
We&#39;re gonna create new
technology that makes this

00:36:52.360 --> 00:36:55.210
previously difficult problem
really, really simple.

00:36:55.210 --> 00:36:57.570
And it might feel small at
first.

00:36:57.570 --> 00:36:59.170
Maybe you&#39;re going after
small businesses and

00:36:59.170 --> 00:37:00.620
then you&#39;re gonna move
upmarket.

00:37:00.620 --> 00:37:02.210
Maybe you&#39;re starting it
just a sliver of

00:37:02.210 --> 00:37:04.170
the use case and then you&#39;re
gonna expand out.

00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:06.500
But you intentionally start
small because you

00:37:06.500 --> 00:37:08.550
will not be able to compete
with an incumbent.

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:10.190
Because the incumbent is
gonna always go for

00:37:10.190 --> 00:37:11.320
the full solution.

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:13.280
So you have to find what are
the gaps in

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:16.600
the full solution that are
significant enough

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:17.620
where a customer is going to

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:20.810
want to solve the problem
with a discreet technology.

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:23.260
But that over time you&#39;re
gonna be able to expand,

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:25.435
again either to larger
customers or

00:37:25.435 --> 00:37:27.600
to more use cases over time.

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:29.130
Great example is zenpayroll.

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:32.119
So zenpayroll, started by a
Stanford graduate or

00:37:32.119 --> 00:37:35.580
Stanford graduates, couple
of years ago.

00:37:35.580 --> 00:37:40.620
Basically discovered that
the payroll process in small

00:37:40.620 --> 00:37:44.190
businesses is an incredibly
complicated and annoying and

00:37:44.190 --> 00:37:45.370
cumbersome process.

00:37:45.370 --> 00:37:47.710
And that&#39;s because we use
the same vendors that we&#39;ve

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:49.470
been using for decades to do
that.

00:37:49.470 --> 00:37:51.630
And they weren&#39;t sort of
digitally oriented.

00:37:51.630 --> 00:37:55.750
You didn&#39;t get your payments
as a receipt, over email.

00:37:55.750 --> 00:37:56.880
It was a very complicated.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:38:00.970
You didn&#39;t really get to see
graphs of your salaries.

00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:03.040
There was no real good data
around this.

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:04.530
And they said, we&#39;re just
gonna take

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:07.920
off the slice that is most
painful to startups around

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:10.820
hiring people and around
paying people,

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:12.840
which is just that payroll
management process.

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:14.160
We&#39;re going to plug into a
lot of

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:15.540
existing infrastructure, but

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:17.710
we&#39;re going to make it dead
simple to go do this.

00:38:17.710 --> 00:38:20.630
And now they&#39;re able to move
both up market over time

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:22.890
as well as deliver new
services over time.

00:38:22.890 --> 00:38:25.640
And what happens is the
incumbents in

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:28.110
this market initially look
at something like this and

00:38:28.110 --> 00:38:29.810
payroll and they say, well,
that&#39;s small.

00:38:29.810 --> 00:38:30.980
It&#39;s only for small
businesses.

00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:32.450
It&#39;s not gonna be very
powerful.

00:38:32.450 --> 00:38:33.900
But that&#39;s just the start.

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:35.540
Because as they get that
wedge and

00:38:35.540 --> 00:38:37.020
as they fit into the market,

00:38:37.020 --> 00:38:38.840
they&#39;re gonna be able to
expand again over time,

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:41.410
build out more services and
more capabilities.

00:38:41.410 --> 00:38:44.330
But they found just the
exact right opening to build

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:46.149
a new company and have that
emerge.

00:38:48.290 --> 00:38:51.550
The next is you really want
to find asymmetries.

00:38:51.550 --> 00:38:54.710
You want to find, my God,
okay, so can we

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:58.660
do like some auto like some
tuning of a voice later so

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:00.490
at least it&#39;ll sound like
I&#39;m doing rap.

00:39:01.800 --> 00:39:03.001
{do things that incumbents
can&#39;t or

00:39:03.001 --> 00:39:04.692
won&#39;t do because it&#39;s
economically or technically

00:39:04.692 --> 00:39:06.417
infeasible} Okay, so you
want to be able to, you want

00:39:06.417 --> 00:39:08.460
to do things that incumbents
can&#39;t or won&#39;t do.

00:39:08.460 --> 00:39:10.280
Because, either the
economics don&#39;t make

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:11.170
sense for them.

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:12.640
Or the economics are so
different, or

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:16.400
so unusual or because
technically they can&#39;t.

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:17.850
I&#39;ll give you two examples.

00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:21.071
So, if you&#39;re gonna build
software today for

00:39:21.071 --> 00:39:24.788
the enterprise that goes
after an incumbent category

00:39:24.788 --> 00:39:27.854
that has more of a sweet
oriented approach.

00:39:27.854 --> 00:39:30.063
Then what you wanna go do,
is you wanna build

00:39:30.063 --> 00:39:32.960
technology that&#39;s gonna be
platform agnostic.

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:35.210
Because what sweet players
will do, is they

00:39:35.210 --> 00:39:38.460
want everything to be
integrated with itself and

00:39:38.460 --> 00:39:41.330
that there&#39;s more value with
that vertical integration.

00:39:41.330 --> 00:39:44.550
But you wanna go after a
different access, which is,

00:39:44.550 --> 00:39:46.480
you want your technology to
work across all of

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:47.670
the platforms.

00:39:47.670 --> 00:39:49.610
So that way, you can work
with so

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:51.330
many different kinds of
customers, and

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:52.810
you can be an ally to so

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:54.370
many different kinds of
platforms,

00:39:54.370 --> 00:39:56.250
which a traditional
incumbent is not able to do.

00:39:56.250 --> 00:39:57.460
So that&#39;s something that is

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:00.810
usually technically
infeasible, because of

00:40:00.810 --> 00:40:02.550
how either something has
been architected.

00:40:02.550 --> 00:40:04.430
Or because the fundamental
component of

00:40:04.430 --> 00:40:07.030
the business model to not do
that as the incumbent.

00:40:08.080 --> 00:40:09.800
But, the other thing is try
and

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:11.230
do things that are
economically infeasible.

00:40:12.520 --> 00:40:14.620
You can look at the cost
structure of

00:40:14.620 --> 00:40:17.630
an incumbent company and
discover where are they

00:40:17.630 --> 00:40:20.010
not going to be able to drop
their prices.

00:40:20.010 --> 00:40:22.370
Because that business model
is fundamental to

00:40:22.370 --> 00:40:24.300
the existence of the
company.

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:28.180
Or where can you find ways
of monetizing the customer

00:40:28.180 --> 00:40:29.802
that are unusual or

00:40:29.802 --> 00:40:33.312
unique, that no one has
discovered before.

00:40:33.312 --> 00:40:35.500
And thus is really not
practical for

00:40:35.500 --> 00:40:36.800
anyone else to do.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:40.110
That&#39;s a company called
Zenefits, where they have

00:40:40.110 --> 00:40:43.010
an HR management software
company that helps you,

00:40:43.010 --> 00:40:44.220
as a small startup,

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:46.940
manage all of your benefits,
all of your HR information.

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:49.830
And instead of charging the
startup, which might not

00:40:49.830 --> 00:40:52.530
value that software at the
stage that they&#39;re at.

00:40:52.530 --> 00:40:53.820
They realized that they
could get

00:40:53.820 --> 00:40:56.690
commission from the
insurance companies.

00:40:56.690 --> 00:40:58.710
And that basically pays for

00:40:58.710 --> 00:41:00.450
the ability to use their
software.

00:41:00.450 --> 00:41:02.030
So, the customer itself is
not paying for

00:41:02.030 --> 00:41:04.900
Zenefits, the Zenefits
platform is being paid for

00:41:04.900 --> 00:41:06.815
by the insurance company.

00:41:06.815 --> 00:41:08.874
And they&#39;ve thus invented a
business model,

00:41:08.874 --> 00:41:10.932
that no other software
company has been able to

00:41:10.932 --> 00:41:11.848
think of or attack.

00:41:11.848 --> 00:41:13.653
And they&#39;re equally going
and

00:41:13.653 --> 00:41:16.431
disrupting a category that
hasn&#39;t seen a lot of

00:41:16.431 --> 00:41:19.279
innovation previously, which
is the health and

00:41:19.279 --> 00:41:22.137
benefit space within small
businesses.

00:41:22.137 --> 00:41:25.504
The next is you wanna find
the really crazy but, but

